You can use the sleep statement in various ways throughout your code, such as delaying a specific action for a short period or waiting for another process to finish before continuing with yours. For instance, if you want your application to wait 5 seconds before displaying an alert message about completing a task successfully, then you could write:
`sleep(5);`
Alternatively, suppose you need to give users time to fill out a form before submitting it to your server; in that case, you could use the following code instead:
```
while (<form field> != null) {
    sleep(2);
}
```
In both examples above, we used simple integers as our duration values. However, you can also specify floating-point numbers or variables instead if needed for more precision or accuracy. For instance, if you want your application to wait exactly 3.14159265358977 seconds before showing the next screen in its interface, then you could write:
`sleep(3.14159265358977);`

You can set the background color using the 'bgcolor' property of your window or any other object. This takes a valid hexadecimal value representing the desired color. For example:
```
bgcolor = #fefef0;
```
This sets the background color to a light yellow (feff0). You can also use this property on global variables, local ones, instances, and references. It works similarly with simple data types like integers or strings. For example:
```
string title = "My Application";
title.bgcolor = #f0ffff;
```

To declare a variable of your choice in Actian 4GL, simply type the name of the variable followed by an equals sign (=) and then the desired value. For example:
i = 5;
This statement declares an integer variable named i and sets its initial value to 5. You can also use this syntax to initialize other types of variables, such as strings or numeric values. The variable name must be unique within its scope (the current frame or the global scope), but you are not limited to using only alphanumeric characters. Any valid identifier will work, including symbols like @ or #. Additionally, you can use the null value (none) for variables that do not have a default value.
